PY  - 1985
Y1  - 1985/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/1884376
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 100
IS  - 3
SP  - 715
EP  - 745
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - A model is presented in which governments can select real expenditure levels that are feasible, but are sufficiently high that a balanced budget is impossible. Thus, governments with large expenditures are committed to inflationary finance schemes. This is the case, even though the governments in question have access to lump-sum taxes. In addition, the model can explain why poorer countries tend to make heavier use of the inflation tax than do wealthier countries, and can account for the existence of country-specific fiat monies.The government that does not have access to the printing press can, nonetheless, use emergency taxes or compulsory loans for emergency financing.S.Fischer [1982, p. 297]
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1884376
ER  - 



